postcontent:
Characteristics for Item # 506990888 		


Manufacturer: 	Husqvarna
Model: 	Lahti P40
Caliber: 	9mm Luger (9x19 Para)
Barrel Length: 	4 inch


Description for Item # 506990888 		

Swedish Lahti m40 9mm Pistol. Stock # MMH282003. Serial # 429xx. This is a 9MM Swedish Model m40 9mm semi-auto pistol, sometimes referred to as a “Lahti” Pistol. Made in Sweden by Husqvarna, this was the standard Swedish Military sidearm from the 1940’s to Post-WWII. The Lahti is a unique semi-auto pistol, in that the trigger has an accellerator in it that allows the pistol to be fired in sub-zero conditions. The pistol has a blue factory finish and brown plastic checkered factory grips with the Hsqvarna logo. There are faint importers markings on the right front of the receiver, the Husqvarna markings are crisp and legible. The magazine is not marked. The pistol has heavy holster wear, wear on the grip straps, service marks, and there is a large spot of discoloration on top of the slide. The grips show minimal wear. The pistol has a nice, crisp bore, good rifling, and a smooth trigger pull. We do not have a box, holster, or any other accessories for this gun.

title: For Sale:  Beretta BM62/69 308 Win. Folder
postcontent: After World War II, Italy adopted the US-designed M1 Garand rifle in .30-06 Springfield (7.62×63mm) and also manufactured it under license. This semi-automatic rifle proved itself well during World War II, but in the late 1950s it was considered outdated and obsolete and the Italian military also wanted a new rifle chambered for the NATO-standard 7.62×51mm round. To meet these requirements, Beretta designed the BM59, which was essentially a rechambered M1 fitted with a removable 20-round magazine, folding bipod and a combined flash suppressor/rifle grenade launcher. The BM59 is capable of selective fire. The BM59 was adopted in 1959 and served with Italian, Argentinian, Indonesian, and Moroccan armies. In the early 1980s, semi-automatic versions were imported to the United States and sold to private collectors.

title: For Sale:  Springfield 1903.
postcontent:
From my personal collection of WWI and WWII military rifles is this great example of Springfield Model 1903 in 30-06 caliber. This particular rifle is Model 1903-A3 made by Smith Corona Typewriter Company back in January 1944. Subcontractor barrels give high collector value to these 234,580 rifles. Serial numbers 3608000 to 3707999 and 4708000 to 4992000 carry the Smith-Corona name on the receiver ring.
It had been assembled by Smith Corona with 4-groove barrel manufactured by High Standard. Those barrels proved to be very accurate, and I did 1/2 inch groups at 50 yards bench rest with my target hand loads. Other guns have 2-groove barrels.
It is hard to come across gun like this these days, as contemporary hunters and shooting enthusiasts value the rifle for its beauty, dependability, and adaptability for almost all U.S. game animals, and with proper gunsmithing, the M1903 makes a wonderful sporting rifle, comparing favorably with many modern firearms. Authentic examples of Smith-Corona rifles, especially with excellent barrels are uncommon for sell, and are in collector's hands.
This rifle has excellent bore, chamber and muzzle. Absolutely no rust or corrosion. No cracks or splits in the wooden parts. Inspector's cartouche is by EmcF. It has small Ordnance Escutcheon and a circled serif "P" is present inside the pistol grip. It is hard to create a clear photo image from the right side of stock. Bolt extractor has "S" marks and Bolt has square Safety Lug, Arrowhead on top of Bolt Handle and single Digit under Bolt Handle (this is normal for Smith-Corona bolts). Receiver is marked "US Smith-Corona 03-A3 and serial number), Barrel is marked "S C" over "Flaming Bomb" and "8 43".Butt plate is Smith-Corona, and is checkered with 11 lines per inch.
Shipping is $39.
Payment by MO or Check.

title: Want To Buy:  Newbie Training
postcontent: I had a .357 revolver and a Mossberg 500 about 30 years ago, and that's the last time I shot a firearm.  I have re-armed with a 9mm Walther PPX, a Stag Arms AR-15 and a semi-auto 12 ga.  I want to start getting range time in to get comfortable again, but I don't want to go alone the first time and just "figure it out", looking like a moron and pissing everyone off.
